# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1899-brooklyn-superbas-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1899-brooklyn-superbas-season] The **1899 Brooklyn Superbas season** was the 16th season of the current-day Dodgers franchise and the ninth season in the National League.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1899-brooklyn-superbas-season] The team won the National League pennant with a record of 101–47, eight games ahead of the Boston Beaneaters, after finishing tenth in 1898.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1899-brooklyn-superbas-season] The 1899 season began with the Brooklyn team and the Baltimore Orioles merging their ownership groups.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1899-brooklyn-superbas-season] Baltimore owner Harry Von der Horst and Ned Hanlon became part owners of Brooklyn.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1899-brooklyn-superbas-season] Von der Horst insisted that Hanlon become the team's new manager, a position that had been promised to outfielder Mike Griffin, who had been interim manager the previous year.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1899-brooklyn-superbas-season] Griffin quit and wound up suing the team for lost wages.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1899-brooklyn-superbas-season] His contract was sold to the Cleveland Spiders, but Griffin never played or managed in the majors again.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1899-brooklyn-superbas-season] Renamed the **Superbas** as part of the deal, the team also siphoned off several of the Orioles' best players.
[src:1899-brooklyn-superbas-season/1899-brooklyn-superbas-season] This influx of talent was a good part of the reason why the Superbas won the National League pennant with 101 wins after winning just 54 games in 1898.
